Introduction

The objective of this project is to explore the contributing factors in determining the quality of the coffee bean. The quality of coffee bean is scored as the cupping score as a standarized scale and in this data set will be labeled as the total_cup_points. The cupping form is where we score coffee on a standardized scale—with points usually ranging from 6-10 in ten different categories such as Fragrance/Aroma, Flavor, Body, Acidity, and Balance. These scores get summed together to get a final score, usually in the 80-90 range. I will explore the most significant predictors for the quality of bean, whether there is any specific predictors that play as the most significant component in predicting the quality of coffee bean. I will use aroma, flavor, aftertaste, acidity, body, balance, uniformity, clean-cup, sweetness, cupper points and moisture as the predictors in the model.

country_table<-coffee_ratings %>%
    count(country_of_origin = factor(country_of_origin)) %>% 
    mutate(pct = prop.table(n)) %>%
    arrange(-pct) %>% 
    tibble()

ggplot(
  country_table %>% filter(country_of_origin != "NA"),
  mapping = aes(
    x = reorder(country_of_origin, n),
    y = pct,
    group = 1,
    label = scales::percent(pct)
  )
) +
  theme_fivethirtyeight() +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",
           fill = "#634832") +
  geom_text(position = position_dodge(width = 0.9),
            # move to center of bars
            hjust = -0.05,
            #Have Text just above bars
            size = 2.5) +
  labs(x = "Country of Origin",
       y = "Proportion of Dataset") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(
    angle = 90,
    vjust = 0.5,
    hjust = 1
  )) +
  ggtitle("Country of Origin Listed in Coffee Ratings Dataset " ) +   # This Emoji messes up this line in R markdown but hey, it
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +                        # looks good.
  coord_flip()

From the graph, it can be inferred that over 45% of coffee bean is produced by Latin America countries, suc as Mexico, Colombia, Guatemala and Brazil. Then, we will see, how the proportion of the species of the coffee bean. Between robusta and arabica, which one more popular.

Getting the year data

coffee_ratings$new_dates<-coffee_ratings$grading_date %>% mdy()

Data set for vizualisation

  top_annual_score<- coffee_ratings %>%
  group_by(species,
           score_year,
           country_of_origin) %>% 
  summarise(max_points = max(total_cup_points)) %>% 
  filter(max_points == max(max_points)) %>% 
  arrange(-max_points)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'species', 'score_year'. You can override
## using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(top_annual_score,
       mapping=aes(x=score_year,
                   y=max_points,
                   label=paste0(score_year,"\n",country_of_origin,"\n", max_points),
                   color=country_of_origin))+
  theme_fivethirtyeight()+
  geom_text(position = position_dodge(width = 0.9),
            # move to center of bars
            hjust =-0.2,
            #Have Text just above bars
            size =3.5) +
  geom_point(size=4,
             alpha=0.8)+
  theme(legend.position = "none")+
  facet_wrap(~species)+
  ggtitle(" Top Scoring Coffees by Year - Faceted on Species ")

The graph give us a glimpse of the production of the coffee bean year by year based on the species (Robusta and Arabica). Arabica beans from Ethiopia scored the highest with a score of 90.58 and for Robusta Beans Uganda had the highest score of 83.75.
